The Basics Correlation Tests
Terminology
Correlation is not necessarily causation (spurious correlations).
Correlation tests yield two
measurements:
r value (measure of correlation)
r 1
(strong, positive correlation)
r 0 (no correlation)
r 1 (strong, negative
correlation)
p value (measure of statistical
signicance)
Get a feeling for it on Guess The Correlation.

The Basics Regression Models
Terminology
- The Intercept. The value of y
when x = 0 (also referred to as
0
).
i
- The Correlation Coefcient.
The increase in y for a one-unit
increase in dependent variable i
(usually, x if only one dependent
variable).
- The Random Error. The
deviation of data points from the
regression line. Usually assumed
to follow N (0,
2
)
Modied after Knut Helge Jensen.

The Basics Regression Models
Assumptions in Theory
Linear regression models need to be inspected for violations of assumptions
after regressing:
Linearity - Residuals vs. Fitted values
Non-linear patterns identify a non-linear relationship between dependent
and independent variables.
Normality - Normal Q-Q plot
Non-normal distribution of residuals shows that the assumption of
N(0,
2
) is violated.
Homoscedasticity - Scale Location
Non-constant variance shows that the assumption of homoscedasticity
(invoked by least squares tting) is violated.
Outliers - Residuals vs. Leverage
A non-zero trend identies the presence of inuential outliers.

The Basics Regression Models
Normality
Normal distributions are common in nature.
Normal/Gaussian distributions are important because:
Easy to do Math with
Common in nature:
Processes which add uctuations create dampening
Dampened uctuations create Gaussian distributions
Information reduced to mean and variance
Underlying process cant be inferred from the distribution
Models which are mechanisitically wrong can still excell in predictive power.

The Basics Regression Models
Homoscedasticity
Variance contains important information.
Variation is at the heart of biology:
Abiotic variation governs biological processes and patterns
Biological variation can alter how ecosystem function and persist
Ignoring variance is a cardinal sin.

The Basics Regression Models
Assumptions in R
Simply type plot(...) with ... denoting your regression model.
You can also target individual plots:
1. plot(..., 1) (Residuals/Fitted)
2. plot(..., 2) (Normal Q-Q plot)
3. plot(..., 3) (Scale Location)
4. plot(..., 4)
(Residuals/Leverage)
By Knut Helge Jensen.

Methods & Models Single Linear Regression
Purpose & Assumptions
Single linear regression
lm() in base R
Purpose: Identify whether and how two variables are related.
Assumptions:
Down to Study-Design:
Response variable is continuous (ratio or interval scale)
Predictor variable is continuous (ratio or interval scale)
Variable values are independent (not paired)
Need for Post-Hoc Tests:
Variable values follow homoscedasticity (equal variance
across entire data range)
Residuals follow normal distribution (normality)
Absence of inuential outliers
Response and Predictor are related in a linear fashion
Aarhus University Biostatistics - Why? What? How? 16 / 36

Methods & Models Mixed Effect Models
Purpose & Assumptions
Linear mixed effect model
lme() in base nlme package
Purpose: Identify whether and how variables are related.
Assumptions:
Down to Study-Design:
Response variable is continuous (ratio or interval scale)
Predictor variables are continuous (ratio or interval scale)
and/or categorical (metric or ordinal scale)
Need for Post-Hoc Tests:
Variable values follow homoscedasticity (equal variance
across entire data range)
Residuals follow normal distribution (normality)
Absence of inuential outliers
Response and Predictor are related in a linear fashion

Methods & Models Mixed Effect Models
Purpose & Assumptions
Linear mixed effect model
lme() in base nlme package
Purpose: Identify whether and how variables are related.
Assumptions:
Down to Study-Design:
Response variable is continuous (ratio or interval scale)
Predictor variables are continuous (ratio or interval scale)
and/or categorical (metric or ordinal scale)
Need for Post-Hoc Tests:
Variable values follow homoscedasticity (equal variance
across entire data range)
Residuals follow normal distribution (normality)
Absence of inuential outliers
Response and Predictor are related in a linear fashion

Methods & Models Mixed Effect Models
Fixed vs. Random Effects
Fixed effects and random effects are also referred to as xed effect factors and
random effect factors.
Fixed Effects:
Informative factor levels regarding
hypothesis.
Want to study these levels and
their effects.
Factor levels are deliberate part of
the study-design.
Higher sample size 6= higher
number of levels.
Random Effects:
Uninformative factor levels
regarding hypothesis.
Do not want to study these levels
and their effects.
Factor levels are imposed by
nature/type of study.
Usually: higher sample size =
higher number of levels.
Usually stored in R in factor mode/class.

Methods & Models Mixed Effect Models
Example - The Model
library(nlme)
MultiLin_Base <- lme(weight ~ Time
*
Diet, # weight as an interaction of time and diet
random = ~+1|Chick, # random effect of Chick
data = ChickWeight)
We now have our model. However, we know that time is a component and we likely have repeated samples here. In these cases, we need to account for
auto-correlation by dening a correlation structure.
MultiLin_Mod <- lme(weight ~ Time
*
Diet, random = ~+1|Chick,
cor=corAR1(), # adding autocorrelation structure since we have repeated measures
data = ChickWeight)
Lets see which model (basic or the one with auto-correlative structure) performs better:
anova(MultiLin_Base, MultiLin_Mod) # second model is better
## Model df AIC BIC logLik Test L.Ratio p-value
## MultiLin_Base 1 10 5487 5530 -2734
## MultiLin_Mod 2 11 4457 4505 -2217 1 vs 2 1032 <.0001
We clearly prefer the more sophisticated, auto-correlative model and want to see which of its parameters are informative:
anova(MultiLin_Mod) # all parameters should be kept
## numDF denDF F-value p-value
## (Intercept) 1 524 485.8 <.0001
## Time 1 524 1436.8 <.0001
## Diet 3 46 3.5 0.0219
## Time:Diet 3 524 24.9 <.0001
We keep all parameters. Although the inclusion of Diet is not signicant, the interaction of Diet and Time is, therefore, both Time and Diet need to stay
irrespective of their signicance.

Methods & Models Mixed Effect Models
Example - Model Output Explained
Variance between chicks (0.006581) is smaller than residual variance (42.46).
This is good!
A chick is expected to have a weightof 40.4165 at Time = 0 and Diet = 1.
Per time-step, weight is expected to increase by 6.0637.
Mean chick weight is different to (read: Diet1 weights are smaller by) Diet
= 1 by -0.8794, -2.1932, and -1.0109 for Diet = 2, Diet = 3, and Diet = 4
respectively (take note that these differences arent statistically signicant).
For Diet = 2, weight of chicks increases, on average, by 2.2077 units more
per one-unit increase in time when compared to Diet = 1. The same logic
applies to Diet = 3, and Diet = 4.

Methods & Models Generalised Linear Models
Example - Model Output Explained
According to this model, a male PhD student without kids and 0 prestige
produces an estimated amount of 0.6228 papers during their PhD studies.
For an increase in prestige by 1, the number of papers increases by 0.0295
(this is not statistically signicant). Unfortunately, being a women brings the
average publication number down by -0.6993. Having kids also has an adverse
effect of reducing the publication number by -0.1258 per kid. Lastly, an increase
in prestige has more benecial impacts on female PhD students as it increases
their publication number per one-increase in prestige by 0.1265 from the
baseline.
Do keep in mind that there are some issues that this model hasnt addressed
yet. Especially, something we call zero-ination of our response variable data
as well as some predictor variable data.

Choosing the Right Method
Choices, Choices, Choices. . .
Linear Model
lm
. When all assumptions are met (i.e.: homoscedasticity,
normality, independence).
Linear Mixed Effect Model
lme
. When the assumption of independence
is violated.
Generalized Linear Model glm. When the assumptions of
homoscedasticity and normality are violated.
Generalized Linear Mixed Effect Model
glmmPQL
from
MASS
, or
glmer
from
lme4
. When the assumptions of homoscedasticity, normality, and
independence are violated.
